{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"a2e8a93b1c9b4fd6","type":"text","text":"Pre-order should be followed up with a Purchase Order for more structure in the accounting control of the DLsoftware.","x":-3520,"y":4310,"width":438,"height":110},
		{"id":"b39fd68042e693cb","type":"text","text":"Pre Order\n\nGunnar or Toni makes a pre-order on a motorcycles brand portal (OEM system).\n\nIn the motorcycle overview (in the dealer portal), it is not possible to see the VIN number (no unique identification), only the chassis, model, color, etc. Therefore, Gunnar must create a temporary (dummy) product with a product id number in DL. When the MC has a VIN number, the 'Swedish Transport Agency' can register the motorcycle. Once the motorcycle is registered (after the purchase is done), the temporary product is replaced with the real product, and the temporary product number is replaced with the registration number.\n\n---\nWhat is a Pre Order:\n\nA **motorcycle preorder** (in OEM portal terms) is:\n\n> A reservation of a future production unit (model + spec).\n\nIt is usually:\n- Done inside the OEM’s ordering system\n    \n- Linked to allocation or production planning\n    \n- Not always a classic “purchase order document”\n\n","x":-3854,"y":3250,"width":452,"height":890},
		{"id":"8c6904b574002dab","type":"text","text":"Purchase Order\n\nPre order are supposed to be followed up with a Purchase order but isn't always done so by the sales department. This creates problems for Monica \n\n---\nWhat is a Purchase Order:\n\nA **Purchase Order (PO)** is:\n\n> A formal document a buyer sends to a supplier saying  \n> “I officially commit to buying this product at this price.”\n\nIt is a **legal purchasing commitment**.\n\nA PO normally includes:\n\n- Supplier name\n    \n- Product (model or SKU)\n    \n- Quantity\n    \n- Agreed price\n    \n- Delivery terms\n    \n- Payment terms\n    \n- PO number (internal reference)\n    \n\nImportant:\n\nA PO is created by the **buyer**, not the supplier.\n\nIt's also created in the DLsoftware system.\n","x":-3220,"y":3250,"width":520,"height":830},
		{"id":"f4ac686c161ce84a","type":"text","text":"Insurance can be handled both before / after the purchase agreement.\n\nAVA MC files the insurance through Bilsport & MC or Svedea). If the customer don't agree with the fee, they can fix the insurance themselves. \n\n---\nThe motorcycle needs to have a VIN number before insurance can be tied to the vehicle.\n\nHowever.\n\nYou can give an 'insurance quote', prepare 'policy terms', 'pre-approve customer'.\n\nBut you cannot activate a binding vehicle-specific insurance policy without VIN.","x":-2308,"y":2766,"width":395,"height":484},
		{"id":"640eef8c16e788e1","type":"text","text":"Registration at Transportstyrelsen (through Bilvision) and done after the purchase (when down payment is paid and vehicle is fully financed) (through LF Finans\n\n---\nThat is largely correct — but let’s refine it.\n\nWith Swedish Transport Agency:\n\nYou need:\n\n- VIN\n    \n- Valid insurance (traffic insurance must be active)\n    \n- Ownership transfer completed\n    \n- Financing approved (if applicable)    \n\nIn practice, most Swedish MC dealers:\n\n1. Secure financing approval\n    \n2. Secure down payment\n    \n3. Activate insurance (effective delivery date)\n    \n4. Register vehicle\n    \n5. Deliver\n\nImportant detail:\n\nRegistration cannot legally be finalized unless traffic insurance is active.\n\nSo insurance technically comes before or simultaneously with registration.","x":-2378,"y":3501,"width":535,"height":831},
		{"id":"5926f5c2f748868d","type":"text","text":"Warranties are registered through the MC brand's portal","x":-2348,"y":4400,"width":475,"height":75},
		{"id":"ea9b56240f1bcf7d","type":"text","text":"Motorcycle delivery arrives at AVA MC and gets registered in 'The recieval of products' (Mottagning av produkter) within the DL system. Monica checks that the 'delivery note' matches the order. (Look more into detail about this process)\n\n---\nInvoices to the supplier are paid (Ask monica when that is?).","x":-3520,"y":4644,"width":438,"height":276},
		{"id":"b97acbd7ebcde20c","type":"text","text":"Motorcycle is now ready to be delivered to the customer. Either they pick it up from the store or AVA MC delivers the vehicle to the customer.","x":-3520,"y":5035,"width":438,"height":125},
		{"id":"0722b0f80fbce421","type":"text","text":"Financial background check (through LF Finans)With LF Finans, you’re dealing with:\n\n- Credit approval\n    \n- Financing contract\n    \n- Often down payment processing\n    \n- Sometimes payout to dealership\n    \n\nThe credit check should happen:\n\n👉 **Before you consider the deal firm.**\n\nRecommended timing:\n\nAfter:\n\n- Customer signs preliminary purchase agreement\n    \n- Final price is defined\n    \n- Model and configuration are defined\n\nBut before:\n\n- You order a non-refundable unit\n    \n- You register vehicle\n    \n- You activate insurance\n\nBecause:\n\nUntil financing is approved, the deal is not real.\n\n---\nWhen the financing of the bike is approved, the customer pays the down payment (20%) (through LF finans as well).","x":-2335,"y":1881,"width":448,"height":819},
		{"id":"6a53fc670aa10f94","type":"text","text":"Existing User Journey of Customer buying a Motocycle @ AVA MC","x":-3640,"y":-480,"width":530,"height":60},
		{"id":"23f853073542e387","type":"text","text":"Purchase Agreement is signed. AVA MC starts to make the motorcycle ready for delivery","x":-3514,"y":2220,"width":250,"height":140},
		{"id":"ad04705af0a7862d","type":"text","text":"MC in stock?","x":-3878,"y":2522,"width":250,"height":60},
		{"id":"7ed7a99536e10651","type":"text","text":"Purchase Agreement contains:\n\nSales person:\n- Name\n- Phone\n- E-mail\n\nVehicle:\n- Type of vehicle\n- New / Used bike\n- Color\n- Manifacture & Model\n- Year model\n- Chassi number\n- Reg.nr\n- Meter setting\n- Warranty\n- Delivery date\n- Delivery conditions\n\nTraded in Vehicle:\n - Information about the traded in vehicle\n\nGoods specification:\n- Vehicle price\n- Sales mission (Försäljningsuppdrag) / Trade in (inbyte) / Customer sell of motorcycle (Kundförsäljning av MC) /Customer purchase of motorcycle (Kundköp av MC)\n- Delivery costs\n- Discount\n- Total cash price\n\nInsurance: \n- Omfattning (Hel/Halv/Trafik/Garage)\n- Omfattning (Helår/Halvår/Kvartal/Konto)\n\nPayment:\n- Downpayment according to seperate receipt (20% I think?)\n- Traded in vehicle (after tax)\n- Cash payment by deliverance according to seperate reciept\n- Credit amount (amount of money you're eligable to loan from the bank (through LF Finans))\n\nFinancing:\n- Bank rate,\n- Arrangement / Structuring fees\n- payment notice fee\n\nSigning Contract:\n- Buyer signs (CIty, Date, Signature)\n- Seller sign (City, Date, Signature)","x":-3766,"y":677,"width":754,"height":1378},
		{"id":"2cfb97dcab2eb722","type":"text","text":"Customer can try out the bike by filling in a 'test driving card'. They fill in a official permit on paper. AVA doesn't put the customer information into the system before the test ride materializes into a potential purchase.","x":-3387,"y":-360,"width":480,"height":160},
		{"id":"158533464be25be5","type":"file","file":"Key things Customer wants to know before committing.md","x":-4212,"y":277,"width":400,"height":400},
		{"id":"eb99199bfe8289c2","type":"text","text":"Questions customer may want to have answered before committing to a potential purchase?","x":-4152,"y":58,"width":280,"height":130},
		{"id":"c06864436cf07d9e","type":"text","text":"When offer is accepted, the purchase agreement is created.\n\n","x":-3514,"y":347,"width":250,"height":113},
		{"id":"b92a584e09e0e98f","type":"text","text":"Customer is interestad in buying the bike? an **Offer ** is created.\n\nAn offer (offert) contains:\n- Customer information\n- Motorcycle costs\n- Spare parts / Equipment costs","x":-3514,"y":-15,"width":250,"height":275},
		{"id":"f155d06cb035e436","type":"text","text":"Customer shows interest in buying a bike through:\n- Coming in to the store directly.\n- Blocket annons / AVA MC website itself (which blocket annons i connected to). This usually end up with email correspondance.","x":-3872,"y":-360,"width":465,"height":200},
		{"id":"64c00569055a485d","type":"text","text":"Order spare parts / equipment (Mattias or Göran in the Service department does that)\n\nMonica orders clothes and stuff to keep the storage stock in balance (since she looks through the order history and service personel don't)","x":-2960,"y":2840,"width":374,"height":214},
		{"id":"4e13f9960d488379","type":"text","text":"How Gunnar orders the bike:\n\nGunnar has an overview of which motorcycles they have ordered through Kawasaki’s dealer portal, for example. He contacts them by email if he has a customer who wants a motorcycle by a specific date. If the motorcycle is in the pre-order list, he may check whether it can be delivered on the date the customer wants.\n\nOtherwise, Gunnar orders the motorcycle via pre-order.","x":-4444,"y":2880,"width":554,"height":240},
		{"id":"ec24f989a7a364e6","type":"text","text":"MC not in stock?","x":-3320,"y":2522,"width":250,"height":60},
		{"id":"cce7d1b7ecf263b9","type":"text","text":"Order the MC (Toni or Gunnar does that)","x":-3567,"y":2655,"width":357,"height":50},
		{"id":"3afc0548545243d9","type":"text","text":"Make it ready for deliverance (look closer into how that looks like?)","x":-3878,"y":2655,"width":250,"height":103},
		{"id":"ff6cdef6f3258a20","type":"text","text":"Process in 'AVA MC Seller Notes 28-1'","x":-2960,"y":3100,"width":374,"height":60},
		{"id":"80ca04ffd4aa17a4","x":-1680,"y":2808,"width":400,"height":400,"type":"file","file":"Insurance Quotes, Policy terms and Pre-approved customer.md"},
		{"id":"810c850027580faa","type":"text","text":"Which of these questions can be answered before a Purchase Agreement is in place?","x":-4212,"y":800,"width":400,"height":82},
		{"id":"84102c530b9acb98","x":-1887,"y":-831,"width":420,"height":60,"type":"text","text":"My Core flows & User Journey"},
		{"id":"a04f69fd19175656","x":-1887,"y":-624,"width":420,"height":288,"type":"text","text":"Core flow:\n\n“From initial interest to signed offer and generated purchase agreement.”\n\nor\n\n\"Help customers explore, evaluate, and commit to a motorcycle purchase by delivering a transparent, risk-aware offer — ending with an accepted purchase agreement.\"\n\n\n\n\n\n"},
		{"id":"adc5145dcc6636cb","x":-1980,"y":-236,"width":607,"height":1476,"type":"text","text":"User Journey\n\n**1. Customer Initiates Interest**\n\n- Customer visits dealership or browses online ads (website or Blocket)\n    \n- Customer expresses interest in a specific motorcycle model or general category\n    \n\n---\n\n**2. Customer Exploration & Risk Evaluation**\n\nCustomer seeks answers about:\n\n- **Financial risks:** Total cost, payment options, insurance estimates\n    \n- **Mechanical risks:** Reliability, maintenance costs, warranty\n    \n- **Emotional risks:** Fit with lifestyle, brand trust, aesthetics\n    \n\nTools/support provided:\n\n- Detailed product info and specs\n    \n- Option to book test rides (with a digital permit form)\n    \n- Insurance cost calculator (customer enters basic info for personalized quotes)\n    \n- Financing calculator and explanation of payment terms\n    \n\n---\n\n**3. Offer Preparation by Salesperson**\n\n- Salesperson gathers customer details and preferences\n    \n- Compiles all costs: motorcycle price, accessories, spare parts, estimated insurance, financing terms\n    \n- Prepares a formal offer document digitally (viewable and shareable)\n    \n\n---\n\n**4. Customer Review & Acceptance**\n\n- Customer reviews the offer on device or printed format\n    \n- Customer accepts via secure digital signature (e.g., BankID) or signed document\n    \n\n---\n\n**5. Handoff to Purchase Agreement Phase**\n\n- Accepted offer triggers purchase agreement preparation (handled by another team/phase)\n    \n- All offer details automatically flow into purchase agreement for consistency\n\n---\n**Key Features for Your Software in This Phase**\n\n- **Interactive product and risk info pages**\n    \n- **Test ride request & permit generation**\n    \n- **Insurance cost estimation tool**\n    \n- **Financing calculator**\n    \n- **Digital offer builder with cost breakdowns**\n    \n- **Secure digital acceptance (BankID or e-signature)**\n    \n- **Automatic handoff/export of accepted offer to next phase**"},
		{"id":"df7de3f8b0f21c7d","x":-720,"y":-771,"width":760,"height":651,"type":"text","text":"Great — this is a **very realistic dealership flow**, especially for an authorized dealer using a DMS (Dealer Management System) and integrations for finance and insurance.\n\nI’ll structure this in a way you can directly use in a presentation or system design document.\n\n---\n\n# 🔵 Core Flow (Offer Phase)\n\nInstead of:\n\n> “Customer wants to know more about the motorcycle before purchase”\n\nI’d refine it to something more decision-oriented:\n\n### ✅ Core Flow Statement:\n\n**“Customer evaluates a specific motorcycle and requests a personalized offer.”**\n\nOr slightly more business-oriented:\n\n**“From initial interest to signed offer and generated purchase agreement.”**\n\nThis clearly defines:\n\n- Start → Interest in a specific bike\n    \n- End → Offer accepted & purchase agreement initiated"},
		{"id":"848535642ee3e3d0","x":-774,"y":40,"width":868,"height":6166,"type":"text","text":"# 🗺 User Journey – Offer Phase\n\nBelow is a clean, structured journey divided into logical stages.\n\n---\n\n# 1️⃣ Interest & Discovery\n\n### Entry Points:\n\n- Customer visits dealership showroom\n    \n- Customer browses dealership website\n    \n- Customer finds bike on Blocket\n    \n- Customer calls dealership about specific motorcycle\n    \n\n### System Touchpoints:\n\n- Website listing\n    \n- CRM lead capture\n    \n- Salesperson registers prospect in DMS\n    \n\n### Customer Goal:\n\n> “Is this the right bike for me?”\n\n### Risks in This Phase:\n\n- Emotional uncertainty\n    \n- Lack of information\n    \n- Trust in dealership\n    \n\n---\n\n# 2️⃣ Product Evaluation (Reducing Mechanical & Emotional Risk)\n\nCustomer now wants full transparency.\n\n### Customer Questions:\n\n- Service history?\n    \n- Warranty?\n    \n- Previous owners?\n    \n- Condition?\n    \n- Included accessories?\n    \n- Known issues?\n    \n- Delivery time?\n    \n\n### System Flow:\n\nSalesperson opens motorcycle object in DMS:\n\n- VIN lookup\n    \n- Service history\n    \n- Reconditioning status\n    \n- Stock status\n    \n- Accessories attached to vehicle\n    \n- Warranty options\n    \n\n### Risk Mitigation:\n\n|Risk Type|How We Reduce It|\n|---|---|\n|Mechanical Risk|Service protocol, inspection checklist, warranty options|\n|Emotional Risk|Test ride booking, comparison tool, salesperson consultation|\n|Brand Trust|Authorized dealership status|\n\n---\n\n# 3️⃣ Financial Evaluation (Reducing Financial Risk)\n\nNow we move into the critical part.\n\n### Customer Thought:\n\n> “Can I afford this — both now and long-term?”\n\n### 3.1 Purchase Options\n\n- Cash\n    \n- Financing (loan)\n    \n- Trade-in\n    \n- Private lease (if applicable)\n    \n\n### 3.2 Finance Calculation Flow\n\nCustomer provides:\n\n- Personal number\n    \n- Employment status\n    \n- Income\n    \n- Down payment\n    \n- Loan duration preference\n    \n\nSystem:\n\n- Credit check integration\n    \n- Monthly cost calculation\n    \n- Interest rate proposal\n    \n- Residual value (if applicable)\n    \n\n---\n\n# 4️⃣ Insurance Calculation\n\nThis is often overlooked but extremely important in Sweden.\n\n### Customer Inputs:\n\n- Personal number\n    \n- Address\n    \n- Parking situation\n    \n- Annual mileage\n    \n- License age\n    \n\nSystem integrates with:\n\n- Insurance provider API\n    \n\nReturns:\n\n- Monthly insurance cost\n    \n- Coverage level options\n    \n\nThis reduces:\n\n- Financial risk\n    \n- Future ownership anxiety\n    \n\n---\n\n# 5️⃣ Offer Configuration (Core of Your Flow)\n\nNow we enter YOUR main responsibility.\n\n### Offer Builder Includes:\n\n#### Customer Information:\n\n- Name\n    \n- Personal number\n    \n- Address\n    \n- Contact details\n    \n\n#### Motorcycle:\n\n- Model\n    \n- VIN\n    \n- Price\n    \n- Mileage\n    \n\n#### Add-ons:\n\n- Spare parts\n    \n- Equipment\n    \n- Riding gear\n    \n- Extended warranty\n    \n- Service package\n    \n\n#### Financial Structure:\n\n- Down payment\n    \n- Monthly payment\n    \n- Loan terms\n    \n- Insurance estimate\n    \n\n#### Trade-in (if applicable):\n\n- Trade-in valuation\n    \n- Settlement of previous loan\n    \n\n---\n\n# 6️⃣ Offer Presentation\n\nOffer is:\n\n- Sent via email\n    \n- Presented digitally\n    \n- Reviewed physically in store\n    \n\nCustomer sees:\n\n- Total price\n    \n- Monthly cost\n    \n- Breakdown of items\n    \n- Terms & conditions\n    \n- Validity date of offer\n    \n\n---\n\n# 7️⃣ Offer Acceptance\n\nCustomer approves by:\n\n- BankID digital signing\n    \n- Written signature in store\n    \n\nOnce accepted:\n\n### System Action:\n\n- Offer status → Accepted\n    \n- Motorcycle status → Reserved/Sold\n    \n- Trigger: Create Purchase Agreement\n    \n- Trigger: Notify colleague responsible for contract phase\n    \n\n⛔ This is where your flow ends.\n\n---\n\n# 📊 Visual Core Flow (Simplified)\n\n1. Interest in motorcycle\n    \n2. Product evaluation\n    \n3. Financial calculation\n    \n4. Insurance calculation\n    \n5. Offer configuration\n    \n6. Offer review\n    \n7. Offer accepted → Purchase agreement created\n    \n\n---\n\n# 🎯 Risks Throughout the Journey\n\nYou can impress your teacher/client by including this layer:\n\n|Risk Type|Where It Appears|How System Handles It|\n|---|---|---|\n|Financial Risk|Finance & insurance stage|Credit check, monthly calculator|\n|Mechanical Risk|Product evaluation|Inspection documentation, warranty|\n|Emotional Risk|Entire journey|Transparency, test ride, comparisons|\n\n---\n\n# 🔄 If You Want It Even More \"Core Flow Oriented\"\n\nHere’s a system-centered version:\n\n1. Lead Created\n    \n2. Motorcycle Selected\n    \n3. Customer Data Captured\n    \n4. Finance Calculation Generated\n    \n5. Insurance Quote Retrieved\n    \n6. Offer Generated\n    \n7. Offer Signed\n    \n8. Purchase Agreement Triggered"},
		{"id":"ed25d98641c54d53","x":-720,"y":-1920,"width":520,"height":920,"type":"text","text":"Question to ChatGPT:\n\nHey chat, you're an expert on the motorcycle world and everything that revolves around it as well DLsoftware. I'm doing a project for a authorized motorcycle dealership and have made journey map over the customer purchase process.\n\nHowever!\n\nNow. I'm making my own coreflow and user journey out of what I've mapped out in the image. SInce my group and I have taken different parts of the purchasing process, I'm doing the offer part. So what I'm focusing on is from the start where the customer shows interest in a bike up until when offer is accepted and purchase agreement is created.\n\nSO! my core flow should be something in the lines of: ''Customer wants to know more about the motorcycle before purchase'. (Feel free to come up with a better wording of that sentence). Then we have a user journey where it starts with the customer showing interest by either coming in to bike shop or looking through the adverts on the website (or blocket). then they would want to know all the ins and outs of the motorcycle, which means the Financial risk (can I afford it?), the mechanical risk (will this break of cost me later?), emotional risk (am I maing the right choice?). Also don't forget about the insurance part, which means that we need to have a section where the customer types in some information in order to find out what the insurance cost will be. Then when the customer hopefully are set about whether or not they can afford to buy the motorcycle, the offer is created. The offer contains customer information, motorcycle costs, spare parts / equipment etc. When the offer is accepted (by BankID or written approval) then we go over to create a purchase agreement and that's what my colleage is working on so that's where my user journey ends. \n\nPlease help me structure a user journey from this information above."},
		{"id":"f1924ff60b469422","x":785,"y":-1760,"width":250,"height":50,"type":"text","text":"Offer Phase - FLowchart"},
		{"id":"5ca2d7b457b6a849","x":510,"y":-1560,"width":800,"height":1480,"type":"text","text":"[Start: Customer Interested in Motorcycle] (Oval)\n         |\n         v\n[Customer discovers bike via showroom, website, or Blocket] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Customer wants full info: specs, service history, accessories] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Reduce Mechanical & Emotional Risk] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Customer evaluates financial situation] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Decision: Can customer afford it?] (Diamond)\n   /        \\\n  Yes        No\n  |           \\\n  v            v\n[Proceed to Insurance Calculation] (Rectangle)   [Customer explores other options] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Customer provides info for insurance quote] (Parallelogram)\n         |\n         v\n[System returns insurance cost & coverage options] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Offer Configuration] (Rectangle)\n   - Customer Info\n   - Motorcycle Price & Details\n   - Add-ons: spare parts, gear, warranty\n   - Finance & Insurance Terms\n         |\n         v\n[Offer Presented to Customer] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[Decision: Offer Accepted?] (Diamond)\n   /        \\\n  Yes        No\n  |           \\\n  v            v\n[Offer Status → Accepted; trigger purchase agreement] (Oval)   [Negotiate / revise offer] (Rectangle)\n         |\n         v\n[End: Offer Accepted → Purchase Agreement Created] (Oval)\n\n---\nThis flowchart captures:\n\n- Entry points (showroom, website, Blocket)\n    \n- Evaluation & risk mitigation (mechanical, emotional, financial)\n    \n- Insurance integration\n    \n- Offer creation & acceptance\n    \n- Clear end point: hand-off to purchase agreement"},
		{"id":"6a3cc87b0970fbf1","x":1680,"y":-1560,"width":1897,"height":1324,"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Let’s turn your flow into a **full UX / service design journey map** for the **offer phase**. I’ll structure it in the classic journey map format with these layers:\n\n1. **Customer Stage / Step** – What the customer is doing\n    \n2. **Touchpoints / Channel** – Where this happens (digital, in-store, phone, etc.)\n    \n3. **Customer Thoughts & Goals** – What they’re thinking or trying to achieve\n    \n4. **Pain Points / Risks** – Friction they might feel\n    \n5. **Opportunities / Design Actions** – How the dealership or system can support them\n    \n\n---\n\n#  Offer Phase UX / Service Journey Map\n\n| Stage                                | Customer Actions                                                       | Touchpoints / Channel                                 | Customer Thoughts & Goals                    | Pain Points / Risks                                                | Opportunities / Design Actions                                                                       |\n| ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Interest / Discovery**             | Browses bikes online, sees ads, or visits showroom                     | Website, Blocket, Showroom, Phone                     | “Is this the right bike for me?”             | Overwhelmed by options, unsure about authenticity                  | Highlight popular models, provide clear photos, videos, and stock info, integrate lead capture forms |\n| **Product Evaluation**               | Checks specs, service history, accessories, warranty                   | DMS, Salesperson consultation, VIN lookup             | “Will this bike be reliable and worth it?”   | Unclear service history, fear of hidden issues                     | Show detailed inspection reports, warranty info, offer test rides, clear comparison tables           |\n| **Financial Evaluation**             | Considers purchase options: cash, loan, trade-in                       | Finance calculator, CRM, in-store consultation        | “Can I afford this now and in the future?”   | Confusing payment terms, hidden costs                              | Interactive monthly cost calculator, transparent loan & trade-in options, pre-fill forms from CRM    |\n| **Insurance Calculation**            | Inputs personal info to see insurance cost                             | Insurance API integration, website or in-store tablet | “How much will it cost to insure this bike?” | Uncertainty about coverage, extra paperwork                        | Auto-populate insurance forms, instant quotes, visually compare coverage levels                      |\n| **Offer Creation**                   | Reviews configured offer with motorcycle, add-ons, finance & insurance | Digital offer, email, in-store print                  | “Does this offer meet my needs?”             | Complexity, lack of clarity in terms, fear of missing hidden costs | Show clear breakdown: bike, add-ons, finance, insurance; interactive editable offer builder          |\n| **Offer Review & Acceptance**        | Reviews, negotiates (if needed), accepts offer                         | Digital signature (BankID), in-store signing          | “Am I ready to commit?”                      | Confusion about signing process, delays in approval                | Step-by-step guided acceptance, BankID integration, confirmation email & PDF receipt                 |\n| **Transition to Purchase Agreement** | Dealership triggers contract creation                                  | DMS, CRM                                              | “I’ve made the right choice”                 | None (handoff phase)                                               | Smooth transition, notify contract team, pre-fill all offer info into agreement                      |\n\n---\n\n### 💡 Key Notes for UX Design:\n\n- **Risks Layer**: Include financial, mechanical, and emotional risk awareness at every stage.\n    \n- **Digital & Physical Integration**: Customers can start online but might end up in-store — ensure seamless handoff.\n    \n- **Transparency & Trust**: Clear information on inspection, insurance, and financing reduces drop-off.\n    \n- **Interactive Tools**: Monthly cost calculator, insurance quote, and editable offer builder increase confidence.\n    \n\n---"},
		{"id":"0fb8a1cfc02724b9","x":2369,"y":-1735,"width":520,"height":50,"type":"text","text":"**Full UX / service design journey map** for the **offer phase**"}
	],
